message.content:
The start symbol expands as  

S → NT15 NT2  

NT15 has only lexical productions (‘t6’, ‘t8’, ‘t0’, ‘t3’, ‘t4’, ‘t9’) – i.e. it can produce exactly one token.  
Therefore the very first token of the whole string must be one of those six, and the remainder of the string (here 22 tokens) has to be derived by NT2.

The given string begins with

t3 t1 …

So the first token ‘t3’ can indeed be produced by NT15 via NT15 → ‘t3’.  
After that, NT2 must derive the rest of the string, whose first token is now ‘t1’.

Examine all possibilities for the first token produced by NT2:

1. Lexical productions of NT2: ‘t9’, ‘t6’, ‘t8’, ‘t3’ – none yield ‘t1’.  
2. Binary productions of NT2:

   • NT2 → NT0 NT14 (first token comes from NT0)  
     NT0 can give ‘t1’, but then NT14 must supply the next token.  
     NT14 can only be ‘t6’ or ‘t9’, yet the actual next token is ‘t7’. ⇒ impossible.

   • NT2 → NT22 NT13 (first token from NT22)  
     NT22 → ‘t1’ matches, and NT13 can give ‘t7’, so the pair ‘t1 t7’ fits;  
     however this rule produces exactly those two tokens and nothing more, so NT2’s
     total length would be 2, not the required 22. ⇒ impossible.

   • NT2 → NT4 NT19 (first token from NT4)  
     NT4 never yields ‘t1’. ⇒ impossible.

Thus NT2 cannot generate any string whose first token is ‘t1’ unless that string is exactly two tokens long (‘t1 t7’). Our required remainder has 22 tokens, so NT2 cannot produce it.

Since NT2 cannot derive the needed suffix, the whole string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No
